problem_solution_en:
[Analysis and Solution] This problem examines the conical pendulum motion and the critical condition of static friction, combined with the analysis of moment balance and the periodicity of simple harmonic motion.
(1) Find the critical static friction coefficient $\mu_0$:
- Moment balance: The tension moment of B is balanced with the gravity moment of A, giving $m_A = m_B$;
- Vertical support force: The support force of the groove bottom on the thin rod is $N = (m_A + m_B)g = 2m_Bg$;
- Critical static friction force: When B is at the rightmost/leftmost position, the horizontal component of the tension is maximum $f_{\max} = T\sin\theta = m_Bg\tan\theta$;
- Static friction coefficient: $\mu_0 = \frac{f_{\max}}{N} = \frac{1}{2}\tan\theta$.

(2) Derive the functional relationship of $\mu(t)$:
- Angular velocity of the conical pendulum: $\omega = \sqrt{\frac{g}{l\cos\theta}}$;
- Instantaneous static friction force: The horizontal component varies cosinusoidally with time $f = |T\sin\theta \cdot \cos\omega t| = |m_Bg\tan\theta \cdot \cos\omega t|$;
- Proportional coefficient: $\mu = \frac{f}{N} = \frac{1}{2}\tan\theta \cdot |\cos\left(\sqrt{\frac{g}{l\cos\theta}} \cdot t\right)|$.
